The Independent Petroleum Marketers Association of Nigeria (IPMAN) has commended the federal government for the slash of petroleum pump price from N145 to N125 per liter, describing the decision as timely. The group has however in a statement signed by its national president, Alhaji (ENGR) Sanusi Fari, called on the government to give its members time to dispose of their old stocks to avert imminent collapse of their investments. “We are grateful to President Muhammadu Buhari for approving the reduction. It will help in alleviating some burden on the masses,” the national president of the group, Alhaji Sanusi had said in the statement. “We equally thank the Hon. Minister of state for petroleum Resources, Chief Timipre Sylva for his prompt advice to Federal Government on the need to low the price of PMS in line with the falling price of crude oil in the international market.” The group, who also expressed gratitude to the Group Managing Director (GMD) of NNPC, Mele K. Kyari for his immediate response, promised to abide to the new price regime. They have however appealed to the government to “through the department of petroleum resources (DPR) and other relevant agencies to allow Independent Marketers to exhaust their old stock at the shortest possible time to avert imminent collapse of our investment due to anticipated losses. “We call on our members to continue to serve the public in the interest of the generality of the populace.” 